teenth and early twentieth centuries. The river helped to shape the future of technocratic knowledge, and the bodies of those who inhabited rural communities were transformed through the environmental intimacies of their daily lives. At the root of this investigation lies the notion that the Nile is not a singular entity, but a realm of practice and a set of temporally, spatially, and materially specific relations that structured experiences of colonial economy. From the microscopic to the regional, the local to the imperial, The Lived Nile recounts the history and centrality of the environment to questions of politics, knowledge, and the lived experience of the human body itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAgriculturexEconomic aspectszEgyptxHistory. 0aDamsxEnvironmental aspectszEgyptxHistory. 0aIrrigation engineeringzEgyptxHistory. 0aIrrigation farmingxHealth aspectszEgyptxHistory. 0aRiver engineeringzEgyptxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Egypt (see also Ancient / Egypt).2bisacsh  aNile River.  acolonial economy.  adam.  aengineering.  ahookworm.  airrigation.  apellagra.  apublic health.  aschistosomiasis.  asubjectivity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311069228040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360966240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503609662423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503609662.